description: The elimination by an organism of the waste products that arise as a result of metabolic activity. These products include water, carbon dioxide (CO2), and nitrogenous compounds.

name: forebrain radial glial cell differentiation
description: The process in which neuroepithelial cells of the neural tube give rise to radial glial cells, specialized bipotential progenitors cells of the forebrain. Differentiation includes the processes involved in commitment of a cell to a specific fate.

name: UDP-glucose catabolic process
description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of UDP-glucose, uridinediphosphoglucose, a substance composed of glucose in glycosidic linkage with uridine diphosphate.

name: body fluid secretion
description: The controlled release of a fluid by a cell or tissue in an animal.

name: negative regulation of phosphoprotein phosphatase activity
description: Any process that stops or reduces the activity of a phosphoprotein phosphatase.

name: positive regulation of phosphoprotein phosphatase activity
description: Any process that activates or increases the activity of a phosphoprotein phosphatase.

name: glutamate catabolic process to 2-oxoglutarate
description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of glutamate into other compounds, including 2-oxoglutarate.

name: glutamate catabolic process to aspartate
description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of glutamate into other compounds, including aspartate.

name: endosome to lysosome transport via multivesicular body sorting pathway
description: The directed movement of substances from endosomes to lysosomes by a pathway in which molecules are sorted into multivesicular bodies, which then fuse with the lysosome.

name: histidine catabolic process to glutamate and formate
description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of histidine into other compounds, including glutamate and formate.

name: negative regulation of protein phosphatase type 2B activity
description: Any process that stops or reduces the activity of the enzyme protein phosphatase type 2B.

name: histidine catabolic process to glutamate and formamide
description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of histidine into other compounds, including glutamate and formamide.

name: positive regulation of protein phosphatase type 2B activity
description: Any process that activates or increases the activity of the enzyme protein phosphatase type 2B.

name: N-acetyl-beta-glucosaminyl-glycoprotein 4-beta-N-acetylgalactosaminyltransferase activity
description: Catalysis of the reaction: UDP-N-acetyl-D-galactosamine + N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosaminyl group = UDP + N-acetyl-beta-D-galactosaminyl-(1->4)-N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosaminyl group.

name: peptidyl-proline modification
description: The modification of peptidyl-proline.

name: protein metabolic process
description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving a specific protein, rather than of proteins in general. Includes protein modification.

name: GABAergic neuron differentiation in basal ganglia
description: The process in which a neuroblast acquires the specialized structural and functional features of a GABAergic inhibitory neuron in the basal ganglia. Differentiation includes the processes involved in commitment of a neuroblast to a GABAergic neuron.

name: pyramidal neuron differentiation
description: The process in which a neuroblast or one of its progeny commits to a pyramidal neuron fate, migrates from the ventricular zone to the appropriate layer in the cortex and develops into a mature neuron.

name: UMP biosynthetic process
description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of UMP, uridine monophosphate.

name: pyramidal neuron migration
description: The migration of pyramidal a neuron precursor from the ventricular zone to the correct layer of the cerebral cortex.

name: cerebral cortex GABAergic interneuron migration
description: The migration of GABAergic interneuron precursors from the subpallium to the cerebral cortex.

name: pyrimidine nucleotide metabolic process
description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving a pyrimidine nucleotide, a compound consisting of nucleoside (a pyrimidine base linked to a deoxyribose or ribose sugar) esterified with a phosphate group at either the 3' or 5'-hydroxyl group of the sugar.

name: hypothalamus development
description: The progression of the hypothalamus region of the forebrain, from its initial formation to its mature state.

name: pyrimidine nucleotide biosynthetic process
description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of a pyrimidine nucleotide, a compound consisting of nucleoside (a pyrimidine base linked to a deoxyribose or ribose sugar) esterified with a phosphate group at either the 3' or 5'-hydroxyl group of the sugar.

name: hypothalamus cell migration
description: The directed movement of a cell into the hypothalamus region of the forebrain.

name: dUMP biosynthetic process
description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of dUMP, deoxyuridine monophosphate (2'-deoxyuridine 5'-phosphate).

name: glycerophosphodiester phosphodiesterase activity
description: Catalysis of the reaction: a glycerophosphodiester + H2O = an alcohol + sn-glycerol 3-phosphate.

name: dUDP biosynthetic process
description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of dUDP, deoxyuridine diphosphate (2'-deoxy-5'-uridylyl phosphate).

name: glycerate kinase activity
description: Catalysis of the reaction: D-glycerate + ATP = 3-phospho-D-glycerate + ADP + 2 H(+).

name: UDP biosynthetic process
description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of UDP, uridine (5'-)diphosphate.

name: maintenance of protein location in cell
description: Any process in which a protein is maintained in a specific location within, or in the membrane of, a cell, and is prevented from moving elsewhere.

name: multicellular organism reproduction
description: The biological process in which new individuals are produced by one or two multicellular organisms. The new individuals inherit some proportion of their genetic material from the parent or parents.

name: sex differentiation
description: The establishment of the sex of an organism by physical differentiation.

name: dosage compensation
description: Compensating for the two-fold variation in X:autosome chromosome ratios between sexes by a global activation or inactivation of all, or most of, genes on one or both of the X chromosomes.

name: DNA duplex unwinding
description: The process in which interchain hydrogen bonds between two strands of DNA are broken or 'melted', generating a region of unpaired single strands.

name: endosome transport via multivesicular body sorting pathway
description: The directed movement of substances from endosomes to lysosomes or vacuoles by a pathway in which molecules are sorted into multivesicular bodies, which then fuse with the target compartment.

name: propionate biosynthetic process
description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of propionate, the anion derived from propionic acid.

name: propionate catabolic process
description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of propionate, the anion derived from propionic acid.

name: developmental process
description: A biological process whose specific outcome is the progression of an integrated living unit: an anatomical structure (which may be a subcellular structure, cell, tissue, or organ), or organism over time from an initial condition to a later condition.

name: muramyl dipeptide binding
description: Interacting selectively and non-covalently, in a non-covalent manner, with muramyl dipeptide; muramyl dipeptide is derived from peptidoglycan.

name: peptidyl-arginine methylation
description: The addition of a methyl group to an arginine residue in a protein.

name: neuroblast division in subventricular zone
description: The division of neuroblasts in the subventricular zone of the forebrain. The interneuron precursors that these cells give rise to include adult olfactory bulb interneurons and migrate tangentially.

name: guanine deaminase activity
description: Catalysis of the reaction: guanine + H2O = xanthine + NH3.

name: glycolate oxidase activity
description: Catalysis of the reaction: glycolate + O2 = glyoxylate + hydrogen peroxide.

name: cell proliferation in forebrain
description: The creation of greater cell numbers in the forebrain due to cell division of progenitor cells.

name: glycine C-acetyltransferase activity
description: Catalysis of the reaction: acetyl-CoA + glycine = L-2-amino-3-oxobutanoate + CoA + H(+).

name: ventricular zone neuroblast division
description: The proliferation of neuroblasts in the ventricular zone of the cerebral cortex. The neuronal progenitors of these cells will migrate radially.

name: dTDP biosynthetic process
description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of dTDP, deoxyribosylthymine diphosphate (2'-deoxyribosylthymine5'-diphosphate).

name: female pregnancy
description: The set of physiological processes that allow an embryo or foetus to develop within the body of a female animal. It covers the time from fertilization of a female ovum by a male spermatozoon until birth.

name: dTMP biosynthetic process
description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of dTMP, deoxyribosylthymine monophosphate (2'-deoxyribosylthymine 5'-phosphate).

name: guanosine-5'-triphosphate,3'-diphosphate diphosphatase activity
description: Catalysis of the reaction: guanosine 5'-triphosphate,3'-diphosphate + H2O = guanosine 5'-diphosphate,3'-diphosphate + phosphate.

name: guanosine-3',5'-bis(diphosphate) 3'-diphosphatase activity
description: Catalysis of the reaction: guanosine 3',5'-bis(diphosphate) + H2O = guanosine 5'-diphosphate + diphosphate.

name: aging
description: A developmental process that is a deterioration and loss of function over time. Aging includes loss of functions such as resistance to disease, homeostasis, and fertility, as well as wear and tear. Aging includes cellular senescence, but is more inclusive. May precede death and may succeed developmental maturation (GO:0021700).

name: cell aging
description: An aging process that has as participant a cell after a cell has stopped dividing. Cell aging may occur when a cell has temporarily stopped dividing through cell cycle arrest (GO:0007050) or when a cell has permanently stopped dividing, in which case it is undergoing cellular senescence (GO:0090398). May precede cell death (GO:0008219) and succeed cell maturation (GO:0048469).

name: dTTP biosynthetic process
description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of dTTP, deoxyribosylthymine triphosphate.

name: embryo implantation
description: Attachment of the blastocyst to the uterine lining.

name: S-adenosylmethionine-homocysteine S-methyltransferase activity
description: Catalysis of the reaction: S-adenosyl-L-methionine + L-homocysteine = S-adenosyl-L-homocysteine + L-methionine.

name: parturition
description: The reproductive process in which the parent is separated from its offspring either by giving birth to live young or by laying eggs.

name: holo-[acyl-carrier-protein] synthase activity
description: Catalysis of the reaction: CoA + substrate-serine = adenosine 3',5'-bisphosphate + substrate-serine-4'-phosphopantetheine. The transfer of the 4'-phosphopantetheine (Ppant) co-factor from coenzyme A to the hydroxyl side chain of the serine residue of acyl- or peptidyl-carrier protein (ACP or PCP) to convert them from the apo to the holo form.

name: UTP biosynthetic process
description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of UTP, uridine (5'-)triphosphate.

name: O-fucosylpeptide 3-beta-N-acetylglucosaminyltransferase activity
description: Catalysis of the transfer of a beta-D-GlcNAc residue from UDP-D-GlcNAc to the fucose residue of a fucosylated protein acceptor.

name: oxalate transmembrane transporter activity
description: Enables the transfer of oxalate from one side of the membrane to the other. Oxalate, or ethanedioic acid, occurs in many plants and is highly toxic to animals.

name: taurine metabolic process
description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving taurine (2-aminoethanesulfonic acid), a sulphur-containing amino acid derivative important in the metabolism of fats.

name: oxalate transport
description: The directed movement of oxalate into, out of or within a cell, or between cells, by means of some agent such as a transporter or pore. Oxalate, or ethanedioic acid, occurs in many plants and is highly toxic to animals.

name: procollagen glucosyltransferase activity
description: Catalysis of the reaction: UDP-glucose + 5-(D-galactosyloxy)-L-lysine-procollagen = UDP + 1,2-D-glucosyl-5-D-(galactosyloxy)-L-lysine-procollagen.

name: toxin transporter activity
description: Enables the directed movement of a toxin into, out of or within a cell, or between cells. A toxin is a poisonous compound (typically a protein) that is produced by cells or organisms and that can cause disease when introduced into the body or tissues of an organism.

name: peptidyl-methionine modification
description: The modification of peptidyl-methionine.

name: peptidyl-lysine modification
description: The modification of peptidyl-lysine.

name: leucine binding
description: Interacting selectively and non-covalently with 2-amino-4-methylpentanoic acid.

name: purine nucleotide metabolic process
description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving a purine nucleotide, a compound consisting of nucleoside (a purine base linked to a deoxyribose or ribose sugar) esterified with a phosphate group at either the 3' or 5'-hydroxyl group of the sugar.

name: midgut development
description: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of the midgut over time, from its formation to the mature structure. The midgut is the middle part of the alimentary canal from the stomach, or entrance of the bile duct, to, or including, the large intestine.

name: maltose alpha-glucosidase activity
description: Catalysis of the reaction: alpha-maltose + H2O = 2 alpha-D-glucose.

name: 24-hydroxycholesterol 7alpha-hydroxylase activity
description: Catalysis of the reaction: (24R)-cholest-5-ene-3beta,24-diol + H(+) + NADPH + O(2) = (24R)-7alpha,24-dihydroxycholesterol + H(2)O + NADP(+).

name: demethylase activity
description: Catalysis of the removal of a methyl group from a substrate.

name: purine nucleotide biosynthetic process
description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of a purine nucleotide, a compound consisting of nucleoside (a purine base linked to a deoxyribose or ribose sugar) esterified with a phosphate group at either the 3' or 5'-hydroxyl group of the sugar.

name: visceral mesoderm-endoderm interaction involved in midgut development
description: The process of cell-cell signaling between visceral mesoderm cells and endoderm cells that is involved in the differentiation of cells in the midgut.

name: cholesterol 24-hydroxylase activity
description: Catalysis of the reaction: cholesterol + H(+) + NADPH + O(2) = (24S)-24-hydroxycholesterol + H(2)O + NADP(+).

name: endoderm development
description: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of the endoderm over time, from its formation to the mature structure. The endoderm is the innermost germ layer that develops into the gastrointestinal tract, the lungs and associated tissues.

name: taurochenodeoxycholate 6alpha-hydroxylase activity
description: Catalysis of the reactions: taurochenodeoxycholate + NADPH + H+ + O2 = taurohyocholate + NADP+ + H2O, and lithocholate + NADPH + H+ + O2 = hyodeoxycholate + NADP+ + H2O.

name: endodermal cell fate determination
description: The cell fate determination process in which a cell becomes capable of differentiating autonomously into an endoderm cell regardless of its environment; upon determination, the cell fate cannot be reversed.

name: mesoderm development
description: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of the mesoderm over time, from its formation to the mature structure. The mesoderm is the middle germ layer that develops into muscle, bone, cartilage, blood and connective tissue.

name: purine-containing compound salvage
description: Any process that generates a purine-containing compound, any nucleobase, nucleoside, nucleotide or nucleic acid that contains a purine base, from derivatives of them without de novo synthesis.

name: AMP biosynthetic process
description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of AMP, adenosine monophosphate.

name: forebrain anterior/posterior pattern specification
description: The creation of specific areas of progenitor domains along the anterior-posterior axis of the developing forebrain.

name: adenine salvage
description: Any process that generates adenine, 6-aminopurine, from derivatives of it without de novo synthesis.

name: ectoderm and mesoderm interaction
description: A cell-cell signaling process occurring between the two gastrulation-generated layers of the ectoderm and the mesoderm.

name: regulation of angiogenesis
description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of angiogenesis.

name: forebrain dorsal/ventral pattern formation
description: The formation of specific regional progenitor domains along the dorsal-ventral axis in the developing forebrain.

name: nucleoside diphosphate phosphorylation
description: The process of introducing a phosphate group into a nucleoside diphosphate to produce a nucleoside triphosphate.

name: positive regulation of adenylate cyclase activity
description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of adenylate cyclase activity.

name: cerebral cortex radially oriented cell migration
description: The migration of cells in the developing cerebral cortex in which cells move from the ventricular and/or subventricular zone toward the surface of the brain.

name: hypoxanthine salvage
description: Any process that generates hypoxanthine, 6-hydroxy purine, from derivatives of it without de novo synthesis.

name: purine ribonucleoside salvage
description: Any process which produces a purine nucleoside from derivatives of it, without de novo synthesis.

name: posterior midgut development
description: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of the posterior midgut over time, from its formation to the mature structure.

name: chemorepulsion of branchiomotor axon
description: The process in which a branchiomotor neuron growth cone is directed to a specific target site in response to a repulsive chemical cue. Branchiomotor neurons are located in the hindbrain and innervate branchial arch-derived muscles that control jaw movements, facial expression, the larynx, and the pharynx.

name: negative regulation of GTP cyclohydrolase I activity
description: Any process that stops or reduces the activity of the enzyme GTP cyclohydrolase I.

name: thalamus development
description: The process in which the thalamus changes over time, from its initial formation to its mature state.

name: negative regulation of asymmetric cell division
description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of asymmetric cell division.

name: cerebral cortex cell migration
description: The orderly movement of cells from one site to another in the cerebral cortex.

name: positive regulation of angiogenesis
description: Any process that activates or increases angiogenesis.

name: cerebral cortex regionalization
description: The regionalization process that results in the creation of areas within the cerebral cortex that will direct the behavior of cell migration and differentiation as the cortex develops.

name: rRNA pseudouridine synthesis
description: The intramolecular conversion of uridine to pseudouridine in an rRNA molecule.

name: L-alanine catabolic process, by transamination
description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of L-alanine by transamination.

name: CBM complex
description: A protein complex comprising Carma1, Bcl10 and MALT1; plays a role in signal transduction during NF-kappaB activation.

name: tRNA pseudouridine synthesis
description: The intramolecular conversion of uridine to pseudouridine in a tRNA molecule.

name: beta-alanine biosynthetic process
description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of beta-alanine (3-aminopropanoic acid), an achiral amino acid and an isomer of alanine. It occurs free (e.g. in brain) and in combination (e.g. in pantothenate) but it is not a constituent of proteins.

name: beta-alanine metabolic process
description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving beta-alanine (3-aminopropanoic acid), an achiral amino acid and an isomer of alanine. It occurs free (e.g. in brain) and in combination (e.g. in pantothenate) but it is not a constituent of proteins.

name: isopeptide cross-linking via N6-(L-isoglutamyl)-L-lysine
description: The formation of an isopeptide cross-link between peptidyl-lysine and peptidyl-glutamine to produce N6-(L-isoglutamyl)-L-lysine.

name: regulation of microtubule polymerization
description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of microtubule polymerization.

name: activin responsive factor complex
description: A transcriptionally active complex that binds to an activin response element (ARE) in the promoter of target genes, and is composed of two SMAD2 proteins, one SMAD4 protein and a Forkhead activin signal transducer (FAST) transcription factor.

name: regulation of microtubule polymerization or depolymerization
description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of microtubule polymerization or depolymerization by the addition or removal of tubulin heterodimers from a microtubule.

name: protein oxidation
description: The modification of a protein amino acid by oxidation.

name: negative regulation of microtubule polymerization or depolymerization
description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of microtubule polymerization or depolymerization.

name: positive regulation of microtubule polymerization
description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of microtubule polymerization.

name: positive regulation of microtubule depolymerization
description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of microtubule depolymerization.

name: DNA hairpin binding
description: Interacting selectively and non-covalently with DNA containing a hairpin. A hairpin structure forms when a DNA strand folds back on itself and intrachain base pairing occurs between inverted repeat sequences.

name: 7alpha-hydroxycholest-4-en-3-one 12alpha-hydroxylase activity
description: Catalysis of the reaction: 7alpha-hydroxycholest-4-en-3-one + H(+) + NADPH + O(2) = 7alpha,12alpha-dihydroxycholest-4-en-3-one + H(2)O + NADP(+).

name: Tle3-Aes complex
description: A transcriptional repressor complex that consists of a heterodimer of the proteins Tle3 (also known as Grg3b) and Aes (Grg5), which are homologs of the Drosophila groucho gene product.

name: protein modification by small protein conjugation
description: A protein modification process in which one or more groups of a small protein, such as ubiquitin or a ubiquitin-like protein, are covalently attached to a target protein.

name: negative regulation of microtubule polymerization
description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of microtubule polymerization.

name: response to cholesterol
description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a cholesterol stimulus.

name: cAMP biosynthetic process
description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of the nucleotide cAMP (cyclic AMP, adenosine 3',5'-cyclophosphate).

name: sodium-dependent organic cation transport
description: The directed, sodium-dependent, movement of organic cations into, out of or within a cell, or between cells, by means of some agent such as a transporter or pore.

name: dADP phosphorylation
description: The process of introducing a phosphate group into dADP, deoxyadenosine diphosphate, to produce dATP.

name: dATP biosynthetic process
description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of dATP, deoxyadenosine triphosphate (2'-deoxyadenosine 5'-triphosphate).

name: 2-alkenal reductase [NAD(P)] activity
description: Catalysis of the reaction: n-alkanal + NAD(P)+ = alk-2-enal + NAD(P)H + H+.

name: ADP biosynthetic process
description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of ADP, adenosine 5'-diphosphate.

name: dADP biosynthetic process
description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of dADP, deoxyadenosine diphosphate (2'-deoxyadenosine 5'-diphosphate).

name: adiponectin binding
description: Interacting selectively and non-covalently with adiponectin, a protein hormone produced by adipose tissue that modulates a number of metabolic processes, including glucose regulation and fatty acid catabolism.

name: receptor metabolic process
description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving a receptor molecule, a macromolecule that undergoes combination with a hormone, neurotransmitter, drug or intracellular messenger to initiate a change in cell function.

name: guanine salvage
description: Any process that generates guanine, 2-amino-6-hydroxypurine, from derivatives of it without de novo synthesis.

name: negative regulation of blood pressure
description: Any process in which the force of blood traveling through the circulatory system is decreased.

name: replication fork arrest
description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of DNA replication by impeding the progress of the DNA replication fork. Replication fork arrest is one of the 'quality control' processes ensuring that DNA-dependent DNA replication occurs correctly. DNA replication fork arrest during DNA-dependent DNA replication is not known to occur outside of cases where a replication error needs to be prevented or corrected.

name: regulation of vascular permeability
description: Any process that modulates the extent to which blood vessels can be pervaded by fluid.

name: positive regulation of axon extension
description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of axon extension.

name: GMP biosynthetic process
description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of GMP, guanosine monophosphate.

name: receptor clustering
description: The receptor metabolic process that results in grouping of a set of receptors at a cellular location, often to amplify the sensitivity of a signaling response.

name: glial cell development
description: The process aimed at the progression of a glial cell over time, from initial commitment of the cell to a specific fate, to the fully functional differentiated cell.

name: negative regulation of vascular permeability
description: Any process that reduces the extent to which blood vessels can be pervaded by fluid.

name: negative regulation of bone resorption
description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of bone resorption.

name: positive regulation of blood pressure
description: Any process in which the force of blood traveling through the circulatory system is increased.

name: postganglionic parasympathetic fiber development
description: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of the postganglionic portion of the parasympathetic fiber over time, from its formation to the mature structure. The parasympathetic fiber is one of the two divisions of the vertebrate autonomic nervous system. Parasympathetic nerves emerge cranially as pre ganglionic fibers from oculomotor, facial, glossopharyngeal and vagus and from the sacral region of the spinal cord. Most neurons are cholinergic and responses are mediated by muscarinic receptors. The parasympathetic system innervates, for example: salivary glands, thoracic and abdominal viscera, bladder and genitalia.

name: branchiomotor neuron axon guidance
description: The process in which a branchiomotor neuron growth cone is directed to a specific target site. Branchiomotor neurons are located in the hindbrain and innervate branchial arch-derived muscles that control jaw movements, facial expression, the larynx, and the pharynx.

name: positive regulation of ossification
description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of bone formation.

name: positive regulation of vascular permeability
description: Any process that increases the extent to which blood vessels can be pervaded by fluid.

name: microtubule polymerization or depolymerization
description: Assembly or disassembly of microtubules by the addition or removal of tubulin heterodimers from a microtubule.

name: 4-hydroxyproline catabolic process
description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of 4-hydroxyproline, C5H9NO3, a derivative of the amino acid proline.

name: melanosome organization
description: A process that is carried out at the cellular level which results in the assembly, arrangement of constituent parts, or disassembly of a melanosome. A melanosome is a tissue-specific, membrane-bounded cytoplasmic organelle within which melanin pigments are synthesized and stored.

name: endosome localization
description: Any process in which endosomes are transported to, and/or maintained in, a specific location within the cell.

name: neurotrophin binding
description: Interacting selectively and non-covalently with a neurotrophin, any of a family of growth factors that prevent apoptosis in neurons and promote nerve growth.

name: positive regulation of bone resorption
description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of bone resorption.

name: tumor necrosis factor binding
description: Interacting selectively and non-covalently with tumor necrosis factor, a proinflammatory cytokine produced by monocytes and macrophages.

name: actin filament bundle
description: An assembly of actin filaments that are on the same axis but may be oriented with the same or opposite polarities and may be packed with different levels of tightness.

name: neuron projection regeneration
description: The regrowth of neuronal processes such as axons or dendrites in response to their loss or damage.

name: filopodium tip
description: The end of a filopodium distal to the body of the cell.

name: D-amino acid catabolic process
description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of D-amino acids, the D-enantiomers of amino acids.

name: positive regulation of phospholipase A2 activity
description: Any process that activates or increases the activity of the enzyme phospholipase A2.

name: response to glucagon
description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a glucagon stimulus.

name: keratan sulfate biosynthetic process
description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of keratan sulfate, a glycosaminoglycan with repeat units consisting of beta-1,4-linked D-galactopyranosyl-beta-(1,4)-N-acetyl-D-glucosamine 6-sulfate and with variable amounts of fucose, sialic acid and mannose units; keratan sulfate chains are covalently linked by a glycosidic attachment through the trisaccharide galactosyl-galactosyl-xylose to peptidyl-threonine or serine residues.

name: L-lysine catabolic process
description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of L-lysine, the L-enantiomer of (S)-2,6-diaminohexanoic acid.

name: animal organ regeneration
description: The regrowth of a lost or destroyed animal organ.

name: activation of phospholipase A2 activity
description: Any process that initiates the activity of the inactive enzyme phospholipase A2.

name: peptide cross-linking
description: The formation of a covalent cross-link between or within protein chains.

name: septin complex
description: A protein complex containing septins.  Typically, these complexes contain multiple septins and are oligomeric.

name: positive regulation of proteasomal ubiquitin-dependent protein catabolic process
description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of the breakdown of a protein or peptide by hydrolysis of its peptide bonds, initiated by the covalent attachment of ubiquitin, and mediated by the proteasome.

name: cuticular plate
description: A dense network of actin filaments found beneath the apical cell surface of hair cells, and into which stereocilia are inserted.

name: axon regeneration
description: The regrowth of axons following their loss or damage.

name: regulation of proteasomal ubiquitin-dependent protein catabolic process
description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the breakdown of a protein or peptide by hydrolysis of its peptide bonds, initiated by the covalent attachment of ubiquitin, and mediated by the proteasome.

name: dendrite regeneration
description: The regrowth of dendrites in response to their loss or damage.

name: negative regulation of proteasomal ubiquitin-dependent protein catabolic process
description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of the breakdown of a protein or peptide by hydrolysis of its peptide bonds, initiated by the covalent attachment of ubiquitin, and mediated by the proteasome.

name: oligodendrocyte cell fate commitment
description: The process in which the developmental fate of a cell becomes restricted such that it will develop into an oligodendrocyte.

name: negative regulation of cell cycle
description: Any process that stops, prevents or reduces the rate or extent of progression through the cell cycle.

name: purine nucleobase catabolic process
description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of purine nucleobases, one of the two classes of nitrogen-containing ring compounds found in DNA and RNA, which include adenine and guanine.

name: positive regulation of I-kappaB kinase/NF-kappaB signaling
description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of I-kappaB kinase/NF-kappaB signaling.

name: smoothened signaling pathway involved in ventral spinal cord interneuron specification
description: The series of molecular signals initiated by binding of a ligand to the transmembrane receptor smoothened in a precursor cell in the ventral spinal cord that contributes to the commitment of the precursor cell to an interneuron fate.

name: positive regulation of cell cycle
description: Any process that activates or increases the rate or extent of progression through the cell cycle.

name: regulation of I-kappaB kinase/NF-kappaB signaling
description: Any process that modulates I-kappaB kinase/NF-kappaB signaling.

name: smoothened signaling pathway involved in spinal cord motor neuron cell fate specification
description: The series of molecular signals initiated by binding of a ligand to the transmembrane receptor smoothened in a precursor cell in the spinal cord that contributes to the process of a precursor cell becoming capable of differentiating autonomously into a motor neuron in an environment that is neutral with respect to the developmental pathway.

name: ErbB-3 class receptor binding
description: Interacting selectively and non-covalently with the protein-tyrosine kinase receptor ErbB-3/HER3.

name: positive regulation of cell adhesion
description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of cell adhesion.

name: purine nucleobase metabolic process
description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving purine nucleobases, one of the two classes of nitrogen-containing ring compounds found in DNA and RNA, which include adenine and guanine.

name: negative regulation of I-kappaB kinase/NF-kappaB signaling
description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of -kappaB kinase/NF-kappaB signaling.

name: oligodendrocyte cell fate specification
description: The process in which a cell becomes capable of differentiating autonomously into an oligodendrocyte in an environment that is neutral with respect to the developmental pathway. Upon specification, the cell fate can be reversed.

name: lateral geniculate nucleus development
description: The progression of the lateral geniculate nucleus over time from its initial formation until its mature state. The lateral geniculate nucleus is the primary processor of visual information received from the retina.

name: motile cilium assembly
description: The aggregation, arrangement and bonding together of a set of components to form a motile cilium.

name: olfactory bulb development
description: The progression of the olfactory bulb over time from its initial formation until its mature state. The olfactory bulb coordinates neuronal signaling involved in the perception of smell. It receives input from the sensory neurons and outputs to the olfactory cortex.

name: guanine catabolic process
description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of guanine, 2-amino-6-hydroxypurine, a purine that is one of the five main bases found in nucleic acids and a component of a number of phosphorylated guanosine derivatives whose metabolic or regulatory functions are important.

name: striatal medium spiny neuron differentiation
description: The process in which a relatively unspecialized cell acquires specialized features of a medium spiny neuron residing in the striatum.

name: surfactant homeostasis
description: Any process involved in the maintenance of a steady-state level of the surface-active lipoprotein mixture which coats the alveoli.

name: plasma membrane part
description: Any constituent part of the plasma membrane, the membrane surrounding a cell that separates the cell from its external environment. It consists of a phospholipid bilayer and associated proteins.

name: inosine catabolic process
description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of inosine, hypoxanthine riboside, a nucleoside found free but not in combination in nucleic acids except in the anticodons of some tRNAs.

name: positive regulation of 1-phosphatidylinositol 4-kinase activity
description: Any process that activates or increases the activity of 1-phosphatidylinositol 4-kinase.

name: regulation of phospholipase A2 activity
description: Any process that modulates the activity of the enzyme phospholipase A2.

name: GBD domain binding
description: Interacting selectively and non-covalently with the GTPase protein binding domain (GDB) domain of a protein. The GBD is a short motif, including a minimum region of 16 amino acids, identified in proteins that bind to small GTPases such as Cdc42 and Rac.

name: glial cell fate commitment
description: The process in which the developmental fate of a cell becomes restricted such that it will develop into a glial cell.

name: ubiquitin binding
description: Interacting selectively and non-covalently with ubiquitin, a protein that when covalently bound to other cellular proteins marks them for proteolytic degradation.

name: positive regulation of cell size
description: Any process that increases cell size.

name: negative regulation of cell volume
description: Any process that decreases cell volume.

name: NAD transport
description: The directed movement of nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide into, out of or within a cell, or between cells, by means of some agent such as a transporter or pore; transport may be of either the oxidized form, NAD, or the reduced form, NADH.

name: negative regulation of cell size
description: Any process that reduces cell size.

name: stereocilium bundle
description: A bundle of cross-linked stereocilia, arranged around a kinocilium on the apical surface of a sensory hair cell (e.g. a neuromast, auditory or vestibular hair cell). Stereocilium bundles act as mechanosensory organelles by responding to fluid motion or fluid pressure changes.

name: C2H2 zinc finger domain binding
description: Interacting selectively and non-covalently with a C2H2-type zinc finger domain of a protein. The C2H2 zinc finger is the classical zinc finger domain, in which two conserved cysteines and histidines co-ordinate a zinc ion.

name: lipase inhibitor activity
description: Stops, prevents or reduces the activity of a lipase, an enzyme that catalyzes of the hydrolysis of a lipid.

name: glycine decarboxylation via glycine cleavage system
description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of glycine by oxidative cleavage to carbon dioxide, ammonia, and a methylene group, mediated by enzymes of the glycine cleavage complex.

name: purine-rich negative regulatory element binding
description: Interacting selectively and non-covalently with a 30-bp purine-rich negative regulatory element; the best characterized such element is found in the first intronic region of the rat cardiac alpha-myosin heavy chain gene, and contains two palindromic high-affinity Ets-binding sites (CTTCCCTGGAAG). The presence of this element restricts expression of the gene containing it to cardiac myocytes.

name: interleukin-23 complex
description: A protein complex that is composed of an interleukin-23 alpha (p19, product of the IL23A gene) and an interleukin-12 beta (p40, product of the IL12B gene) subunit and is secreted into the extracellular space.

name: ligase regulator activity
description: Modulates the activity of a ligase.

name: tubulin-glutamic acid ligase activity
description: Catalysis of the posttranslational transfer of one or more glutamate residues to the gamma-carboxyl group(s) of one or more specific glutamate residues on a tubulin molecule.

name: stereocilium
description: An actin-based protrusion from the apical surface of auditory and vestibular hair cells and of neuromast cells. These protrusions are supported by a bundle of cross-linked actin filaments (an actin cable), oriented such that the plus (barbed) ends are at the tip of the protrusion, capped by a tip complex which bridges to the plasma. Bundles of stereocilia act as mechanosensory organelles.

name: response to interleukin-6
description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of an interleukin-6 stimulus.

name: positive regulation of mismatch repair
description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of mismatch repair.

name: ubiquitin-protein transferase inhibitor activity
description: Stops, prevents or reduces the activity of a ubiquitin-protein transferase.

name: stereocilium tip
description: A distinct compartment at the tip of a stereocilium, distal to the site of attachment to the apical cell surface. It consists of a dense matrix bridging the barbed ends of the stereocilium actin filaments with the overlying plasma membrane.

name: ubiquitin-protein transferase regulator activity
description: Modulates the activity of a ubiquitin-protein transferase, an enzyme that catalyzes the covalent attachment of ubiquitin to lysine in a substrate protein.

name: regulation of mismatch repair
description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of mismatch repair.

name: Golgi to secretory granule transport
description: The directed movement of proteins from the Golgi to a secretory granule. The secretory granule is a membrane-bounded particle, usually protein, formed in the granular endoplasmic reticulum and the Golgi complex.

name: indoleamine 2,3-dioxygenase activity
description: Catalysis of the reaction: tryptophan + O2 = N-formylkynurenine. The product of the reaction depends on the substrate; D-tryptophan produces N-formyl-D-kynurenine, and L-tryptophan produces N-formyl-L-kynurenine.

name: peptidyl-cysteine S-nitrosylation
description: The covalent addition of a nitric oxide (NO) group to the sulphur (S) atom of a cysteine residue in a protein, to form peptidyl-S-nitrosyl-L-cysteine.

name: nucleus accumbens development
description: The progression of the nucleus accumbens over time from its initial formation until its mature state. The nucleus accumbens is a collection of pleomorphic cells in the caudal part of the anterior horn of the lateral ventricle, in the region of the olfactory tubercle, lying between the head of the caudate nucleus and the anterior perforated substance. It is part of the ventral striatum, a composite structure considered part of the basal ganglia.

name: orbitofrontal cortex development
description: The progression of the orbitofrontal cortex over time from its initial formation until its mature state. The orbitofrontal cortex is a cerebral cortex region located in the frontal lobe.

name: amygdala development
description: The progression of the amygdala over time from its initial formation until its mature state. The amygdala is an almond-shaped set of neurons in the medial temporal lobe of the brain that play a key role in processing emotions such as fear and pleasure.

name: regulation of hindgut contraction
description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of muscle contraction of the hindgut, the posterior part of the alimentary canal, including the rectum, and the large intestine.

name: deoxyadenosine catabolic process
description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of deoxyadenosine, 2-deoxyribosyladenine, one of the four major nucleosides of DNA.

name: adenosine catabolic process
description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of adenosine, adenine riboside, a ribonucleoside found widely distributed in cells of every type as the free nucleoside and in combination in nucleic acids and various nucleoside coenzymes.

name: hippocampus development
description: The progression of the hippocampus over time from its initial formation until its mature state.

name: positive regulation of cell volume
description: Any process that increases cell volume.

name: mammillary body development
description: The progression of the mammillary body over time from its initial formation until its mature state. The mammillary body is a protrusion at the posterior end of the hypothalamus that contains hypothalamic nuclei.

name: negative regulation of intestinal cholesterol absorption
description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of uptake of cholesterol into the blood by absorption from the intestine.

name: 3'-5' DNA helicase activity
description: Catalysis of the unwinding of the DNA helix in the direction 3' to 5'.

name: limbic system development
description: The progression of the limbic system over time from its initial formation until its mature state. The limbic system is a collection of structures in the brain involved in emotion, motivation and emotional aspects of memory.

name: DNA replication, removal of RNA primer
description: Removal of the Okazaki RNA primer from the lagging strand of replicating DNA, by a combination of the actions of DNA polymerase, DNA helicase and an endonuclease.

name: substantia nigra development
description: The progression of the substantia nigra over time from its initial formation until its mature state. The substantia nigra is the layer of gray substance that separates the posterior parts of the cerebral peduncles (tegmentum mesencephali) from the anterior parts; it normally includes a posterior compact part with many pigmented cells (pars compacta) and an anterior reticular part whose cells contain little pigment (pars reticularis).

name: positive regulation of chromatin assembly or disassembly
description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of chromatin assembly or disassembly.

name: subthalamic nucleus development
description: The progression of the subthalamic nucleus over time from its initial formation until its mature state. The subthalamic nucleus is the lens-shaped nucleus located in the ventral part of the subthalamus on the inner aspect of the internal capsule that is concerned with the integration of somatic motor function.

name: 5'-3' DNA helicase activity
description: Catalysis of the unwinding of the DNA helix in the direction 5' to 3'.

name: lysosome localization
description: Any process in which a lysosome is transported to, and/or maintained in, a specific location.

name: histone demethylase activity (H4-R3 specific)
description: Catalysis of the removal of a methyl group from arginine at position 3 of the histone H4 protein.

name: negative regulation of sodium:proton antiporter activity
description: Any process that stops or reduces the activity of a sodium:hydrogen antiporter, which catalyzes the reaction: Na+(out) + H+(in) = Na+(in) + H+(out).

name: positive regulation of sodium:proton antiporter activity
description: Any process that activates or increases the activity of a sodium:hydrogen antiporter, which catalyzes the reaction: Na+(out) + H+(in) = Na+(in) + H+(out).

name: ATP-dependent 5'-3' DNA helicase activity
description: Catalysis of the reaction: ATP + H2O = ADP + phosphate; drives the unwinding of the DNA helix in the direction 5' to 3'.

name: ATP-dependent 3'-5' DNA helicase activity
description: Catalysis of the reaction: ATP + H2O = ADP + phosphate; drives the unwinding of the DNA helix in the direction 3' to 5'.

name: single-stranded DNA-dependent ATPase activity
description: Catalysis of the reaction: ATP + H2O = ADP + phosphate; this reaction requires the presence of single-stranded DNA, and it drives another reaction.

name: negative regulation of transporter activity
description: Any process that stops or reduces the activity of a transporter.

name: positive regulation of transporter activity
description: Any process that activates or increases the activity of a transporter.

name: oxidation-reduction process
description: A metabolic process that results in the removal or addition of one or more electrons to or from a substance, with or without the concomitant removal or addition of a proton or protons.

name: peptidyl-cysteine methylation
description: The methylation of peptidyl-cysteine to form peptidyl-S-methyl-L-cysteine.

name: positive regulation of ion transmembrane transporter activity
description: Any process that activates or increases the activity of an ion transporter.

name: histone demethylase activity (H3-R2 specific)
description: Catalysis of the removal of a methyl group from arginine at position 2 of the histone H3 protein.

name: protein-glycine ligase activity
description: Catalysis of the posttranslational transfer of one or more glycine residues to a specific glutamate residue on a target protein.

name: regulation of cardiac muscle contraction
description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of cardiac muscle contraction.

name: protein hydroxylation
description: The addition of a hydroxy group to a protein amino acid.

name: regulation of sodium:proton antiporter activity
description: Any process that modulates the activity of a sodium:hydrogen antiporter, which catalyzes the reaction: Na+(out) + H+(in) = Na+(in) + H+(out).

name: protein-glycine ligase activity, initiating
description: Catalysis of the posttranslational transfer of a glycine residue to the gamma-carboxyl group(s) of one or more specific glutamate residues on a target protein.

name: regulation of ion transmembrane transporter activity
description: Any process that modulates the activity of an ion transporter.

name: negative regulation of cardiac muscle contraction
description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of cardiac muscle contraction.

name: protein adenylyltransferase activity
description: Catalysis of the reaction: ATP + protein = diphosphate + adenylyl-protein; mediates the addition of an adenylyl (adenosine 5'-monophosphate; AMP group) to specific residues of target proteins.

name: peptide-methionine (R)-S-oxide reductase activity
description: Catalysis of the reaction: peptide-L-methionine + H(2)O + thioredoxin disulfide = peptide-L-methionine (R)-S-oxide + thioredoxin. Can act on oxidized methionine in peptide linkage with specificity for the R enantiomer. Thioredoxin disulfide is the oxidized form of thioredoxin.

name: relaxation of cardiac muscle
description: The process in which the extent of cardiac muscle contraction is reduced.

name: histone H3-K27 methylation
description: The modification of histone H3 by addition of one or more methyl groups to lysine at position 27 of the histone.

name: detection of molecule of bacterial origin
description: The series of events in which a stimulus from a molecule of bacterial origin is received and converted into a molecular signal.

name: respiratory burst after phagocytosis
description: A phase of elevated metabolic activity, during which oxygen consumption increases, that occurs in neutrophils, monocytes, and macrophages shortly after phagocytosing material. An enhanced uptake of oxygen leads to the production, by an NADH dependent system, of hydrogen peroxide (H2O2), superoxide anions and hydroxyl radicals, which play a part in microbiocidal activity.

name: positive regulation of integrin biosynthetic process
description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of the chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of integrins.

name: positive regulation of translation
description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of the chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of proteins by the translation of mRNA.

name: response to peptidoglycan
description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a peptidoglycan stimulus. Peptidoglycan is a bacterial cell wall macromolecule.

name: response to muramyl dipeptide
description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a muramyl dipeptide stimulus. Muramyl dipeptide is derived from peptidoglycan.

name: phosphatidylinositol catabolic process
description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of phosphatidylinositol, any glycophospholipid with its sn-glycerol 3-phosphate residue is esterified to the 1-hydroxyl group of 1D-myo-inositol.

name: response to bacterial lipoprotein
description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a bacterial lipoprotein stimulus.

name: negative regulation of integrin biosynthetic process
description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of the chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of integrins.

name: negative regulation of gluconeogenesis
description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of gluconeogenesis.

name: positive regulation of cilium assembly
description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of the formation of a cilium.

name: positive regulation of glycogen biosynthetic process
description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of the chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of glycogen.

name: positive regulation of gluconeogenesis
description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of gluconeogenesis.

name: positive regulation of fatty acid biosynthetic process
description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of the chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of fatty acids.

name: enzyme active site formation via cysteine modification to L-cysteine persulfide
description: The formation of an enzyme active site via modification of peptidyl-cysteine to peptidyl-L-cysteine persulfide.

name: peptidyl-serine octanoylation
description: The octanoylation of peptidyl-serine to form peptidyl-O3-octanoyl-L-serine, typical of the protein ghrelin.

name: peptidyl-amino acid modification
description: The alteration of an amino acid residue in a peptide.

name: regulation of Rap protein signal transduction
description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of Rap protein signal transduction.

name: regulation of Ral protein signal transduction
description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of Ral protein signal transduction.

name: Rap protein signal transduction
description: A series of molecular signals within the cell that are mediated by a member of the Rap family of proteins switching to a GTP-bound active state.

name: regulation of Cdc42 protein signal transduction
description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of Cdc42 protein signal transduction.

name: positive regulation of DNA repair
description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of DNA repair.

name: negative regulation of type I interferon production
description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate, or extent of type I interferon production. Type I interferons include the interferon-alpha, beta, delta, episilon, zeta, kappa, tau, and omega gene families.

name: positive regulation of cyclin-dependent protein serine/threonine kinase activity
description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of CDK activity.

name: negative regulation of DNA repair
description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of DNA repair.

name: regulation of Rab protein signal transduction
description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of Rab protein signal transduction.

name: Ral protein signal transduction
description: A series of molecular signals within the cell that are mediated by a member of the Ral family of proteins switching to a GTP-bound active state.

name: positive regulation of type I interferon production
description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate, or extent of type I interferon production. Type I interferons include the interferon-alpha, beta, delta, episilon, zeta, kappa, tau, and omega gene families.

name: Rab protein signal transduction
description: A series of molecular signals within the cell that are mediated by a member of the Rab family of proteins switching to a GTP-bound active state.

name: positive regulation of protein catabolic process
description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of the chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of a protein by the destruction of the native, active configuration, with or without the hydrolysis of peptide bonds.

name: respiratory burst
description: A phase of elevated metabolic activity, during which oxygen consumption increases; this leads to the production, by an NADH dependent system, of hydrogen peroxide (H2O2), superoxide anions and hydroxyl radicals.

name: nutrient reservoir activity
description: Functions in the storage of nutritious substrates.

name: negative regulation of cyclin-dependent protein serine/threonine kinase activity
description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of cyclin-dependent protein serine/threonine kinase activity.

name: protein polyamination
description: The modification of a protein amino acid by polyamination.

name: anaphase-promoting complex-dependent catabolic process
description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of a protein or peptide by hydrolysis of its peptide bonds, initiated by the covalent attachment of ubiquitin, with ubiquitin-protein ligation catalyzed by the anaphase-promoting complex, and mediated by the proteasome.

name: SCF-dependent proteasomal ubiquitin-dependent protein catabolic process
description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of a protein or peptide by hydrolysis of its peptide bonds, initiated by the covalent attachment of ubiquitin, with ubiquitin-protein ligation catalyzed by an SCF (Skp1/Cul1/F-box protein) complex, and mediated by the proteasome.

name: otolith morphogenesis
description: The process in which the anatomical structures of an otolith are generated and organized.

name: pseudopodium
description: A temporary protrusion or retractile process of a cell, associated with flowing movements of the protoplasm, and serving for locomotion and feeding.

name: regulation of type I interferon production
description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate, or extent of interferon type I production. Type I interferons include the interferon-alpha, beta, delta, episilon, zeta, kappa, tau, and omega gene families.

name: cGMP biosynthetic process
description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of cyclic GMP, guanosine 3',5'-phosphate.

name: dGDP biosynthetic process
description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of dGDP, deoxyguanosine diphosphate, (2'-deoxyguanosine 5'-diphosphate).

name: Golgi calcium ion transport
description: The directed movement of calcium ions (Ca2+) into, out of or within the Golgi apparatus.

name: dGDP phosphorylation
description: The process of introducing a phosphate group into dGDP, deoxyguanosine diphosphate, to produce dGTP.

name: cytoplasmic side of mitochondrial outer membrane
description: The external (cytoplasmic) face of the mitochondrial outer membrane.

name: GTP biosynthetic process
description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of GTP, guanosine triphosphate.

name: positive regulation of endoplasmic reticulum calcium ion concentration
description: Any process that increases the concentration of calcium ions in the endoplasmic reticulum.

name: negative regulation of endoplasmic reticulum calcium ion concentration
description: Any process that decreases the concentration of calcium ions in the endoplasmic reticulum.

name: 'de novo' IMP biosynthetic process
description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of IMP, inosine monophosphate, by the stepwise assembly of a purine ring on ribose 5-phosphate.

name: positive regulation of epidermal growth factor receptor signaling pathway
description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of epidermal growth factor receptor signaling pathway activity.

name: positive regulation of fibroblast growth factor receptor signaling pathway
description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of fibroblast growth factor receptor signaling pathway activity.

name: positive regulation of DNA replication
description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of DNA replication.

name: IMP biosynthetic process
description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of IMP, inosine monophosphate.

name: positive regulation of epidermal growth factor-activated receptor activity
description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of EGF-activated receptor activity.

name: negative regulation of Notch signaling pathway
description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of the Notch signaling pathway.

name: positive regulation of Notch signaling pathway
description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of the Notch signaling pathway.

name: negative regulation of G-protein coupled receptor protein signaling pathway
description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of G-protein coupled receptor protein signaling pathway activity.

name: positive regulation of G-protein coupled receptor protein signaling pathway
description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of G-protein coupled receptor protein signaling pathway activity.

name: regulation of cytokinesis
description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the division of the cytoplasm of a cell and its separation into two daughter cells.

name: sister chromatid biorientation
description: The cell cycle process in which sister chromatids establish stable attachments to microtubules emanating from opposite spindle poles.

name: selenate reductase activity
description: Catalysis of the reaction: 2 e(-) + 2 H(+) + selenate = H(2)O + selenite.

name: negative regulation of cytokinesis
description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of the division of the cytoplasm of a cell, and its separation into two daughter cells.

name: negative regulation of protein homooligomerization
description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of protein homooligomerization.

name: regulation of axon diameter
description: Any process that modulates the rate, direction or extent of axon growth such that the correct diameter is attained and maintained.

name: positive regulation of protein homooligomerization
description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of protein homooligomerization.

name: endoplasmic reticulum calcium ion homeostasis
description: Any process involved in the maintenance of an internal steady state of calcium ions within the endoplasmic reticulum of a cell or between the endoplasmic reticulum and its surroundings.

name: inner mucus layer
description: The inner of two mucus layers secreted by epithelial cells in the colon; the inner mucus layer is firmly attached to the epithelium, is densely packed with a compact stratified appearance and is devoid of bacteria.

name: outer mucus layer
description: The outer of two mucus layers secreted by epithelial cells in the colon; the outer mucus layer is loosely packed and can be colonized by bacteria.

name: positive regulation of cytokinesis
description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of the division of the cytoplasm of a cell, and its separation into two daughter cells.

name: BMP receptor binding
description: Interacting selectively and non-covalently with a BMP receptor.

name: Golgi calcium ion homeostasis
description: Any process involved in the maintenance of an internal steady state of calcium ions within the Golgi apparatus of a cell or between the Golgi and its surroundings.

name: thyroxine 5-deiodinase activity
description: Catalysis of the reaction: 3,3',5'-triiodo-L-thyronine + iodide + A + H+ = L-thyroxine + AH2.

name: ITP catabolic process
description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of ITP, inosine (5'-)triphosphate.

name: negative regulation of action potential
description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of action potential creation, propagation or termination. This typically occurs via modulation of the activity or expression of voltage-gated ion channels.

name: AMP catabolic process
description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of AMP, adenosine monophosphate.

name: positive regulation of protein oligomerization
description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of protein oligomerization.

name: 3alpha,7alpha,12alpha-trihydroxy-5beta-cholestanoyl-CoA 24-hydroxylase activity
description: Catalysis of the reaction: (25R)-3alpha,7alpha,12alpha-trihydroxy-5beta-cholestan-26-oyl-CoA + H2O + acceptor = (24R,25R)-3alpha,7alpha,12alpha,24-tetrahydroxy-5beta-cholestan-26-oyl-CoA + reduced acceptor.

name: purine nucleotide catabolic process
description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of a purine nucleotide, a compound consisting of nucleoside (a purine base linked to a deoxyribose or ribose sugar) esterified with a phosphate group at either the 3' or 5'-hydroxyl group of the sugar.

name: cAMP catabolic process
description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of the nucleotide cAMP (cyclic AMP, adenosine 3',5'-cyclophosphate).

name: negative regulation of Toll signaling pathway
description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of the Tl signaling pathway.

name: inductive cell-cell signaling
description: Signaling at short range between cells of different ancestry and developmental potential that results in one cell or group of cells effecting a developmental change in the other. This is often done by secretion of proteins by one cell which affects the neighboring cells and causes them to adopt a certain fate.

name: positive regulation of action potential
description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of action potential creation, propagation or termination. This typically occurs via modulation of the activity or expression of voltage-gated ion channels.

name: regulation of adenylate cyclase activity
description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of adenylate cyclase activity.

name: RNA 3'-end processing
description: Any process involved in forming the mature 3' end of an RNA molecule.

name: histone demethylase activity (H3-K9 specific)
description: Catalysis of the reaction: histone H3 N6-methyl-L-lysine (position 9) + alpha-ketoglutarate + O2 = succinate + CO2 + formaldehyde + lysine. This reaction is the removal of a methyl group from lysine at position 9 of the histone H3 protein.

name: mRNA 3'-end processing
description: Any process involved in forming the mature 3' end of an mRNA molecule.

name: nerve growth factor processing
description: The generation of a mature nerve growth factor (NGF) by proteolysis of a precursor.

name: ribosomal S6-glutamic acid ligase activity
description: Catalysis of the posttranslational transfer of one or more glutamic acid residues to the C-terminus of ribosomal protein S6.

name: histone demethylase activity
description: Catalysis of the removal of a methyl group from a histone.

name: cytoplasmic microtubule organization
description: A process that is carried out at the cellular level which results in the assembly, arrangement of constituent parts, or disassembly of structures formed of microtubules and associated proteins in the cytoplasm of a cell.

name: histone demethylase activity (H3-K4 specific)
description: Catalysis of the removal of a methyl group from lysine at position 4 of the histone H3 protein.

name: 25-hydroxycholesterol 7alpha-hydroxylase activity
description: Catalysis of the reactions: cholest-5-ene-3beta,25-diol + NADPH + H+ + O2 = cholest-5-ene-3beta,7alpha,25-triol + NADP+ + H2O, and cholest-5-ene-3beta,27-diol + NADPH + H+ + O2 = cholest-5-ene-3beta,7alpha,27-triol + NADP+ + H2O.

name: slow endocytic recycling
description: The directed movement of membrane-bounded vesicles from deep (non-peripheral) compartments endocytic compartments back to the plasma membrane where they are recycled for further rounds of transport.

name: developmental induction
description: A developmental process involving two tissues in which one tissue (the inducer) produces a signal that directs cell fate commitment of cells in the second tissue (the responder).

name: regulation of protein oligomerization
description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of protein oligomerization.

name: rRNA 3'-end processing
description: Any process involved in forming the mature 3' end of an rRNA molecule.

name: endocytic recycling
description: The directed movement of membrane-bounded vesicles from recycling endosomes back to the plasma membrane where they are recycled for further rounds of transport.

name: L-phenylalanine:2-oxoglutarate aminotransferase activity
description: Catalysis of the reaction: L-phenylalanine + 2-oxoglutarate = phenylpyruvate + L-glutamate.

name: fatty acid alpha-hydroxylase activity
description: Catalysis of the conversion of a fatty acid to an alpha-hydroxylated fatty acid. A hydroxyl group is added to the second carbon, counted from the carboxyl end, of a fatty acid chain.

name: regulation of response to stress
description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of a response to stress. Response to stress is a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a disturbance in organismal or cellular homeostasis, usually, but not necessarily, exogenous (e.g. temperature, humidity, ionizing radiation).

name: H4/H2A histone acetyltransferase complex
description: A multisubunit complex that catalyzes the acetylation of histones H4 and H2A.

name: axon initial segment
description: Portion of the axon proximal to the neuronal cell body, at the level of the axon hillock. The action potentials that propagate along the axon are generated at the level of this initial segment.

name: varicosity
description: Non-terminal inflated portion of the axon, containing the specialized apparatus necessary to release neurotransmitters.

name: terminal bouton
description: Terminal inflated portion of the axon, containing the specialized apparatus necessary to release neurotransmitters. The axon terminus is considered to be the whole region of thickening and the terminal bouton is a specialized region of it.

name: dendritic shaft
description: Cylindric portion of the dendrite, directly stemming from the perikaryon, and carrying the dendritic spines.

name: dendritic spine
description: A small, membranous protrusion from a dendrite that forms a postsynaptic compartment - typically receiving input from a single presynapse.  They function as partially isolated biochemical and an electrical compartments. Spine morphology is variable including "thin", "stubby", "mushroom", and "branched", with a continuum of intermediate morphologies. They typically terminate in a bulb shape, linked to the dendritic shaft by a restriction. Spine remodeling is though to be involved in synaptic plasticity.

name: ATP-binding cassette (ABC) transporter complex
description: A complex for the transport of metabolites into and out of the cell, typically comprised of four domains; two membrane-associated domains and two ATP-binding domains at the intracellular face of the membrane, that form a central pore through the plasma membrane. Each of the four core domains may be encoded as a separate polypeptide or the domains can be fused in any one of a number of ways into multidomain polypeptides. In Bacteria and Archaebacteria, ABC transporters also include substrate binding proteins to bind substrate external to the cytoplasm and deliver it to the transporter.

name: amino acid homeostasis
description: Any process involved in the maintenance of an internal steady state of amino acid within an organism or cell.

name: sulfate binding
description: Interacting selectively and non-covalently with sulfate, SO4(2-), a negatively charged small molecule.

name: L-cysteine desulfhydrase activity
description: Catalysis of the reaction: L-cysteine + H2O = ammonia + pyruvate + hydrogen sulfide + H+.

name: DNA demethylation
description: The removal of a methyl group from one or more nucleotides within an DNA molecule.

name: phosphopantetheine binding
description: Interacting selectively and non-covalently with phosphopantetheine, the vitamin pantetheine 4'-(dihydrogen phosphate).

name: neuron projection development
description: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of a neuron projection over time, from its formation to the mature structure. A neuron projection is any process extending from a neural cell, such as axons or dendrites (collectively called neurites).

name: AMP transport
description: The directed movement of AMP, adenosine monophosphate, into, out of or within a cell, or between cells, by means of some agent such as a transporter or pore.

name: AMP transmembrane transporter activity
description: Enables the transfer of AMP, adenosine monophosphate, from one side of a membrane to the other.

name: rRNA methylation
description: The posttranscriptional addition of methyl groups to specific residues in an rRNA molecule.

name: detection of muramyl dipeptide
description: The series of events in which a muramyl dipeptide stimulus is received by a cell and converted into a molecular signal. Muramyl dipeptide is derived from peptidoglycan.

name: response to lipopolysaccharide
description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a lipopolysaccharide stimulus; lipopolysaccharide is a major component of the cell wall of gram-negative bacteria.

name: detection of lipopolysaccharide
description: The series of events in which a lipopolysaccharide stimulus is received by a cell and converted into a molecular signal. Lipopolysaccharide is a major component of the cell wall of gram-negative bacteria.

name: D-alanine catabolic process
description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of D-alanine, the D-enantiomer of the amino acid alanine.

name: C3HC4-type RING finger domain binding
description: Interacting selectively and non-covalently with a C3HC4-type zinc finger domain of a protein. The C3HC4-type zinc finger is a variant of RING finger, is a cysteine-rich domain of 40 to 60 residues that coordinates two zinc ions, and has the consensus sequence: C-X2-C-X(9-39)-C-X(1-3)-H-X(2-3)-C-X2-C-X(4-48)-C-X2-C, where X is any amino acid. Many proteins containing a C3HC4-type RING finger play a key role in the ubiquitination pathway.

name: stress fiber assembly
description: The aggregation, arrangement and bonding together of a set of components to form a stress fiber. A stress fiber is a contractile actin filament bundle that consists of short actin filaments with alternating polarity.

name: induction of bacterial agglutination
description: Any process in which infecting bacteria are clumped together by a host organism.

name: pre-snoRNP complex
description: A ribonucleoprotein complex that contains a precursor small nucleolar RNA (pre-snoRNA) and associated proteins, and forms during small nucleolar ribonucleoprotein complex (snoRNP) assembly. Pre-snoRNP complexes may contain proteins not found in the corresponding mature snoRNP complexes.

name: negative regulation of cysteine-type endopeptidase activity involved in apoptotic process
description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of a cysteine-type endopeptidase activity involved in the apoptotic process.

name: entrainment of circadian clock by photoperiod
